On the 15th August, 1867, the Factory Acts Extension Act, and 
on the 21st August, the Workshops’ Regulation Act received the Royal Assent; 
the former Act having reference to large industries, the latter to small.

How little the increased intensity and extension of labour through piece wages 
benefited the agricultural proletariat, the following passage borrowed 
from a work on the side of the landlords and farmers shows:

Simple reproduction is only the periodical repetition of this first operation; 
each time money is converted afresh into capital. Thus the law is not broken; 
on the contrary, it is merely enabled to operate continuously. “Several 
successive acts of exchange have only made the last represent the first” 
(Sismondi, “Nouveaux Principes, etc.,” p. 70).

Everything therefore depends upon making hunger permanent among the working 
class, and for this, according to Townsend, the principle of population, 
especially active among the poor, provides.

